### *from* the Daybook of Frater Idimon Pentoi

- After the space voyage's freefall and sedentary confinement, my muscles ached
  when I rose this morning, despite the low gravity.  I took an ambling walk
  along the canal front.  I could not recollect myself and remember little from
  the walk save the elbows of the passing Wahazenes.  The main thoroughfare was
  thronged, I thought.  In reality I don't know if it was thronged or barely
  peopled.

- All Wahazenes look to me emaciated, elongated and tall.  Most are two heads or
  more taller than I, yet few are anywhere near as heavy.  Not one is as broad.
  Their garments are both wildly beautiful and wildly slattern.  Every household
  I passed along the streets ... either I saw a warm glow in the windows or
  smelled strange food cooking or listened in passing to subspace radio dramas
  resounding from tinny speakers or the stentorian tones of native priests
  sermonizing in the Jagarôth tongue, which I am here to learn, among many other
  things.  Everyone here however speaks Rago...

- The canal did leave an impression.  The Jagarôth word for water -- *lal* --
  connotes wholesome purity, even "holiness"; the canal's water was stagnant,
  dark and still.  It smelled faintly of latrine and, along one stretch, of
  rotting homin flesh.  Massive armored fish broke the surface to taste the
  buoyant trash.  The Rago word *lalo* of course comes from *lal* but lacks
  connotations.

- I feel that the gulf between the ideal and the reality of Wahazene canal water
  -- between Jagarôth *lal* and Rago *lalo* -- should bother people more.  But
  the Wahazkin I spoke to today do not see with their eyes but instead with
  their opinions.  Not one judged a thing according to *its* nature; they
  consulted only their own inwardness, then pronounced vain judgments concerning
  every manner of thing.  Tomorrow I meet my correspondent and patron here,
  Tatam Miwax.  *Father* Miwax.  The thought of calling any man *Father*
  disturbs me, for I never had one.  I hope his reason is stronger than that of
  the specimens I've met thus far.  His letters hint at wisdom.  I hope it is
  not all egoistic deception...

- I caught an unpleasant chemical odor in one street.  I asked the guide whom
  Tatam Miwax assigned to me what it was.  *Jizix* he said.  A powerful
  stimulant ignited in a glass pipe and the smoke inhaled...
